---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title =
    "BC PNP Express Entry vs Skills Immigration 2026: The Definitive Comparison";
const description =
    "Should you choose Express Entry BC or Skills Immigration? We compare processing times, CLB requirements, and federal PR timelines to help you decide.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
    <article class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 py-12 px-4 sm:px-6">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-8">
            <!-- Header -->
            <header class="space-y-4 text-center">
                <div
                    class="inline-block bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 px-4 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold mb-4"
                >
                    Strategic Choice
                </div>
                <h1
                    class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight"
                >
                    Express Entry <span class="text-green-600">vs</span><br
                    />Skills Immigration
                </h1>
                <p
                    class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed"
                >
                    This is often the first major decision an applicant makes.
                    Choosing the wrong stream can cost you 12+ months of waiting
                    time or result in an automatic rejection.
                </p>
            </header>

            <!-- Quick Comparison -->
            <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                <div
                    class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 p-6 rounded-2xl relative overflow-hidden"
                >
                    <div
                        class="absolute top-0 right-0 bg-blue-600 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-bl-lg"
                    >
                        Fast Track
                    </div>
                    <div class="text-xl font-black text-blue-700 mb-2">
                        Express Entry BC
                    </div>
                    <div class="text-sm text-blue-800 font-medium space-y-1">
                        <p>‚è±Ô∏è ~8 months total</p>
                        <p>üìù Needs active EE profile</p>
                        <p>üó£Ô∏è CLB 7 minimum</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div
                    class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 p-6 rounded-2xl relative overflow-hidden"
                >
                    <div
                        class="absolute top-0 right-0 bg-green-600 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-bl-lg"
                    >
                        Flexible
                    </div>
                    <div class="text-xl font-black text-green-700 mb-2">
                        Skills Immigration
                    </div>
                    <div class="text-sm text-green-800 font-medium space-y-1">
                        <p>‚è±Ô∏è ~18 months total</p>
                        <p>üìù Direct to province</p>
                        <p>üó£Ô∏è CLB 4 minimum</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Main Content -->
            <div
                class="prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm"
            >
                <h2>The Fundamental Difference</h2>
                <p>
                    Both streams end at the same place: Permanent Residence. The
                    difference is the <strong>engine</strong> that gets you there.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Express Entry BC (EEBC):</strong> Is a <em
                            >turbo-charged</em
                        > stream. You must meet Federal standards First (FSW or CEC),
                        then get a provincial boost. The federal government processes
                        your final PR application electronically (fast).
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Skills Immigration (SI):</strong> Is a <em
                            >standard</em
                        > stream. You only need to meet Provincial standards. The
                        federal government processes your final PR application via
                        paper-based/portal upload (slow queue).
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Detailed Comparison Table</h2>

                <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto my-6">
                    <table class="min-w-full text-left text-sm border-collapse">
                        <thead>
                            <tr class="bg-gray-100 border-b border-gray-300">
                                <th
                                    class="p-3 font-bold text-slate-900 border-r border-gray-200"
                                    >Feature</th
                                >
                                <th
                                    class="p-3 font-bold text-blue-800 border-r border-gray-200"
                                    >Express Entry BC</th
                                >
                                <th class="p-3 font-bold text-green-800"
                                    >Skills Immigration</th
                                >
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100">
                            <tr>
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-medium border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Prerequisite</td
                                >
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 text-slate-600 border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Must have active IRCC Express Entry Profile
                                    & Job Seeker Code</td
                                >
                                <td class="p-3 text-slate-600"
                                    >None (Just need BC Job Offer)</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="bg-slate-50">
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-medium border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Language</td
                                >
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 text-slate-600 border-r border-gray-100"
                                    ><strong>Strict CLB 7</strong> (IELTS 6.0+) for
                                    NOC 0,1,2,3</td
                                >
                                <td class="p-3 text-slate-600"
                                    ><strong>Flexible CLB 4</strong> (though higher
                                    helps score)</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-medium border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Education</td
                                >
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 text-slate-600 border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Usually requires ECA (credential
                                    assessment) immediately</td
                                >
                                <td class="p-3 text-slate-600"
                                    >ECA often not needed until later (unless
                                    claiming points)</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="bg-slate-50">
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-medium border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Processing Time (Federal)</td
                                >
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-bold text-green-600 border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >5 - 8 Months</td
                                >
                                <td class="p-3 font-bold text-amber-600"
                                    >15 - 21 Months</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 font-medium border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >Eligible NOCs</td
                                >
                                <td
                                    class="p-3 text-slate-600 border-r border-gray-100"
                                    >TEER 0, 1, 2, 3 only</td
                                >
                                <td class="p-3 text-slate-600"
                                    >TEER 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 (ELSS)</td
                                >
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h2>The "600 Point" Advantage</h2>
                <p>This is why people choose EEBC.</p>
                <p>
                    In the federal Express Entry system, you might have a CRS
                    score of 400 (which is too low to be invited). If you get
                    nominated through <strong>Express Entry BC</strong>, you
                    automatically get <strong>+600 points</strong> added to your federal
                    score.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Your new score becomes 1000. In the next federal draw, you
                    are guaranteed to receive an Invitation to Apply (ITA) for
                    permanent residence.
                </p>

                <h2>Why Would Anyone Choose "Skills Immigration"?</h2>
                <p>
                    It seems slower and worse, right? Not necessarily. Here is
                    why tens of thousands of people choose SI:
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <strong>They don't have CLB 7:</strong> Many skilled tradespeople
                        or service workers have excellent job skills but struggle
                        to get IELTS 6.0 in reading/writing. SI allows them to apply
                        with CLB 4.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>They work in TEER 4/5:</strong> Jobs like long-haul
                        truck drivers, care aides, or food processing workers are
                        often ineligible for Express Entry. SI is their <em
                            >only</em
                        > option.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Work Permit Expiry:</strong> If your work permit is
                        expiring in 2 months and you can't pass the English test yet,
                        you might panic. You can register for SI immediately (if eligible)
                        to get into the pool, whereas EEBC would require waiting for
                        test results first.
                    </li>
                </ol>

                <div
                    class="bg-amber-50 p-6 rounded-xl border border-amber-200 my-8"
                >
                    <h3 class="text-amber-800 font-bold text-lg mb-2">
                        Detailed Timeline Comparison
                    </h3>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div>
                            <span
                                class="block text-xs font-bold text-slate-500 uppercase"
                                >Scenario A: The Fast Track (EEBC)</span
                            >
                            <div
                                class="w-full bg-slate-200 rounded-full h-4 mt-1"
                            >
                                <div
                                    class="bg-blue-600 h-4 rounded-full"
                                    style="width: 40%"
                                >
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div
                                class="flex justify-between text-xs text-slate-600 mt-1"
                            >
                                <span>BC Appl. (2-3 mo)</span>
                                <span>Fed. Appl. (6 mo)</span>
                                <span><strong>Total: ~9 Months</strong></span>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <span
                                class="block text-xs font-bold text-slate-500 uppercase"
                                >Scenario B: The Scenic Route (SI)</span
                            >
                            <div
                                class="w-full bg-slate-200 rounded-full h-4 mt-1"
                            >
                                <div
                                    class="bg-green-600 h-4 rounded-full"
                                    style="width: 90%"
                                >
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div
                                class="flex justify-between text-xs text-slate-600 mt-1"
                            >
                                <span>BC Appl. (3 mo)</span>
                                <span>Fed. Paper Appl. (18 mo)</span>
                                <span><strong>Total: ~21 Months</strong></span>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Can I Switch?</h2>
                <p>
                    <strong>Scenario:</strong> You apply for Skills Immigration because
                    your English is low. Six months later, you retake the test and
                    get CLB 8. Can you switch to Express Entry to speed things up?
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>If not nominated yet:</strong> YES. You can withdraw your
                    SIRS registration and create a new one under EEBC.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>If already nominated:</strong> NO. Once the nomination
                    certificate is issued, it is hard-coded as "Non-Express Entry."
                    You cannot change it. You are stuck in the slow lane unless you
                    withdraw and restart the entire process (risky).
                </p>

                <h2>Decision Matrix</h2>
                <p>Use this logic to decide today:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        If you have <strong>CLB 7+</strong> AND <strong
                            >1 year skilled work exp</strong
                        > ‚Üí <span class="text-blue-700 font-bold"
                            >Pick Express Entry BC.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        If you are working in <strong
                            >Hospitality/Tourism/Entry Level</strong
                        > ‚Üí <span class="text-green-700 font-bold"
                            >Pick Skills Immigration.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        If your <strong
                            >Post-Grad Work Permit expires in 4 months</strong
                        > ‚Üí <span class="text-blue-700 font-bold"
                            >Pick Express Entry BC</span
                        > (Bridging Open Work Permit is easier to get).
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <h3>Is the application fee the same?</h3>
                <p>
                    Yes. The BC PNP fee ($1,475) is identical. The federal fees
                    are also similar ($\$1,500+), but the processing speed is
                    the main value difference.
                </p>

                <h3>Does EEBC have higher cut-off scores?</h3>
                <p>
                    Actually, often <strong>NO</strong>. In many draws, the
                    cut-off score for EEBC and SI is exactly the same. Sometimes
                    EEBC is even slightly <em>lower</em> because the province knows
                    these candidates will be processed faster federally, reducing
                    the burden on provincial support services.
                </p>

                <h3>
                    What happens if my Express Entry profile expires while
                    waiting?
                </h3>
                <p>
                    You must create a new one immediately and update your BC PNP
                    profile with the new Express Entry Profile Number and Job
                    Seeker Code. If you don't, your nomination will fail to
                    transmit.
                </p>
            </div>

            <!-- CTA -->
            <div class="bg-slate-900 text-white p-8 rounded-2xl text-center">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Still Unsure?</h2>
                <p class="text-slate-300 mb-6">
                    Our calculator shows you your score for BOTH streams
                    side-by-side.
                </p>
                <a
                    href="/bc-pnp-calculator"
                    class="inline-block bg-white text-slate-900 font-bold px-8 py-3 rounded-xl hover:bg-slate-200 transition-colors"
                >
                    Compare Scores Now ‚Üí
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>
</BaseLayout>
